[2] USA (Texas): canine, human exposure
Date: Thu 30 May 2013
Source: KTXS/KTXE [edited]
http://www.ktxs.com/news/rabies-case-confirmed-in-dog-at-abilene-animal-shelter-workers-treated-for-exposure/-/14769632/20364418/-/j6ompk/-/index.html


A dog that was housed and on display at Abilene's animal shelter has tested positive for rabies. A worker with an animal charity confirmed he and at least 2 city workers were treated for exposure from the animal.

The puppy was found in the area south of the intersection of County Road 424 and County Road 347 east of Hawley in Jones County.

Authorities are looking for anyone who has been bitten or otherwise exposed to the saliva of the puppy from 5 May until the day it died, 24 May 2013, including those who visited the Animal Shelter on South 25th Street, between last Wednesday and last Friday [22-24 May 2013].

If bitten or exposed, please call (325)-437-4585 and leave your contact information. A member of the Texas Department of State Health Services will call you back with important information.

Christine Mann with the Texas Department of State Health Services said it's vital for people who may have been exposed to see their doctor for treatment.

"Rabies is transmitted through infected saliva. Once symptoms develop , whether in a human or an animal, the disease is almost always fatal," Mann said.

[byline: Jason Goodwin]

